# ğŸ“ Linux File Permissions â€” Numeric Mode (`chmod`)

## ğŸ” What Are File Permissions in Linux?

Every file in Linux has three types of users:
- ğŸ‘¤ **Owner** (user who created the file)
- ğŸ‘¥ **Group** (users in the same group)
- ğŸŒ **Others** (everyone else)

And three types of access:
- `r` â†’ Read
- `w` â†’ Write
- `x` â†’ Execute

---

## ğŸ”¢ Numeric (Octal) Permission System

Permissions are represented by **numbers** (0â€“7), using this rule:

| Permission | Binary | Value |
|------------|--------|-------|
| Read (`r`) | 100    | 4     |
| Write (`w`)| 010    | 2     |
| Execute (`x`) | 001 | 1     |

Add the values to set permissions:

| Access | Binary | Value | Symbolic |
|--------|--------|--------|-----------|
| `rwx`  | 111    | 7      | full access |
| `rw-`  | 110    | 6      | read + write |
| `r--`  | 100    | 4      | read only |
| `r-x`  | 101    | 5      | read + execute |
| `--x`  | 001    | 1      | execute only |
| `---`  | 000    | 0      | no access |

---

## ğŸ§® Structure of `chmod XYZ file`

- X = permission for **Owner**
- Y = permission for **Group**
- Z = permission for **Others**

Example:
```bash
chmod 755 script.sh

#####ğŸ¯ Common chmod Values
Value	Meaning	Symbolic
600 ---	Only owner can read/write	rw-------
644 ---	Owner rw, others read	rw-r--r--
700	--- Only owner can do everything	rwx------
755 ---	Everyone can read/execute, only owner can write	rwxr-xr-x
400 ---	Read-only for owner	r--------
777 ---	Everyone can do everything âš ï¸	rwxrwxrwx
